XPS was performed to determine the elemental composition of the S-C-dots. Two prominent features of C1s and O1s accompanied with two small peaks of S2s and S2p are clearly observed in the survey spectrum (Fig. 4
                        a), indicating the S-C-dots are mainly composed of C and O as well as limited amount of S which may come from WFO and sulfuric acid. The C1s spectrum (Fig. 4b) exhibits five distinct carbon states of CC at 284.1eV, C–C at 284.5eV, C–S at 285.3eV, C–O at 286.5eV, and OC–OH at 289.1eV [45,54]. The O1s spectrum (Fig. 4c) shows the oxygen signals of CO at 531.4eV and C–O at 533.0eV [47]. Two peaks located at 163.9 and 167.9eV in the S2p spectrum (Fig. 4d) suggest two forms of sulfur. The former peak can be resolved into two different components at 163.5 and 164.6eV corresponding to the 2p3/2 and 2p1/2 positions of thiophene-S owing to their spin–orbit coupling [53,56]. The latter peak deconvoluted into three components at 167.6, 168.5 and 169.3eV is associated with some oxidized sulfur such as sulfonate [53]. These results reveal that the sulfur atoms have not only doped into the carbon framework of the nanodots in the form of thiophene, but also functionalized the surface of the nanodots in the state of sulfonate. The elemental analysis demonstrates the composition of the S-C-dots is C 68.55wt%, S 3.79wt%, H 6.12wt%, and O 21.54wt% (calculated), agreeing well with the XPS test. The FTIR spectrum (Fig. 5
                        ) displays the absorption bands of O–H at 3435cm−1, CO at 1715cm−1, CC at 1630cm−1, SO/C–O at 1171cm−1, C–S/C–O at 1043cm−1, and C–H at 2928, 2855, 1461, and 1402cm−1. NMR spectra were measured to further investigate the structural details of the S-C-dots. There are three kinds of chemical environments of protons in the 1H NMR spectrum (Fig. S1a): 1–3ppm for sp3 C–H protons, 3–5ppm for the protons attached with hydroxyl, ether and carbonyl groups, and 6–8ppm for the aromatic protons [57]. The 13C NMR spectrum (Fig. S1b) reveals C–C and C–O/C–S carbons in 0–80ppm, CC alkene/aromatic carbons in 100–140ppm, and CO carboxylic/carbonyl carbons in 170–190ppm. The aqueous solution of the S-C-dots presents a Zeta potential of −55.9mV (Fig. S2), suggesting they are negatively charged due to carboxylic and sulfonic groups on the surface. It is also found that the S-C-dots are highly soluble in hydrophilic solvents (e.g. ethanol and N,N-Dimethylformamide), but poorly soluble in hydrophobic solvents (e.g. ethyl acetate and cyclohexane) despite they contain abundant aliphatic groups (Fig. S3). This result indicates that different from the hydrophilic groups surrounding the surface of the S-C-dots, the hydrophobic aliphatic groups mainly exist in the core of the S-C-dots. Taken together, it is concluded that the as-prepared samples are sulfur-doped, carbon-rich nanodots, which contain aromatic and aliphatic carbons in the core and are functionalized with plentiful hydrophilic groups on the surface.
